<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-02-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-02-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="676" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d676">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/6358: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner at Constantinople</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-02-13"><hi rend="italic">February 13, 1920</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received February
                                    16—2:24 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>130. From Admiral McCully [,Sevastopol.]</p>
                            <p>“16. February 13, 1 a.m. Agreement has been reached between Denikin
                                and Supreme Cossack Council but it is not whole hearted and
                                effective. Terek agrees unreservedly, Don with a ‘perplexed
                                souland’, and Kuban with protest and mental reservations. Conditions
                                in Sevastopol point to repetition of Odessa events at an early
                                date.”</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bristol</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>